<body>
    <h1>The Parabola Mystery:A Quadratic Tale of Symmetry and Curves</h1>
    <div class="container">
        <h2> The Equation</h2>
        <p>
        The <u><i> general</i></u> form of a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_function"> quadratic function </a> is <span class="highlight"> f(x)=ax2+bx+c</span> where a, b, and c are real numbers and a≠0.<br>
        The <u><i> standard</i></u> form of a quadratic function is <span class="highlight">f(x)=a(x−h)2+k</span>.
        <p>
            A quadratic function can thus be expressed as <span class="highlight">y = ax² + bx + c</span>.
            Here, <span class="highlight">a</span> coefficient controls the width and direction (i.e., whether the graph opens up or opens down), 
            <span class="highlight">b</span> coefficient tilts the graph (i.e., controls the skew), and <span class="highlight">c</span> (constant term) shifts it up or down the y-axis. <br>
            <br> <br><br>
            <a href="https://dl.uncw.edu/digilib/mathematics/algebra/mat111hb/functions/manipulate/manipulate.html#sec2"> Learn more on <strong> shifting </strong> </a>
            <br> <br> 
            <i>Watch</i>: <a href="https://youtu.be/wW6O5uYwMZY?si=rzPSQc_DJh92gTAe" >
            How to find the <emp> Ditection of a parabola</emp> </a>
        </p>

        <h2> Why a Parabola?</h2>
        <p>
            The <span class="highlight">x²</span> term <i> (squared variable) </i> means that as x increases or decreases, the change in y gets faster and faster (it accelerates), creating the curved "U" shape.
            
            The curve is <a href="https://study.com//learn/lesson/recognizing-symmetry-about-x-axis-y-axis.html#:~:text=A%20graph%20is%20symmetrical%20along,f%20(x%2C%20y).&text=The%20graph%20above%20depicts%20a%20line%20equation." >
            symmetric</a> about a vertical line, called the <strong> <a href="https://www.cuemath.com/algebra/axis-of-symmetry/">
            axis of symmetry</a></strong>. This is because, we know that a graph is symmetrical along the X-axis if it contains two points (x, y) and (x, -y) such that f (x, y) = f (x, -y) and squaring a positive and negative x gives the same y-value.
            Hence, <emp> squaring a number creates a symmetric relationship:
            both positive and negative x give the same y (since <span class="highlight">(-x)² = x²</span>).<emp>
            This symmetry forms a curved "U" shape which is known as a <i> <b> <a href="https://study.com//learn/lesson/parabolic-shape.html#:~:text=A%20parabola%20is%20a%20curve,%3Dx%5E2%2B1."> Parabola </a></b> </i>.
        
            As x gets larger, the change in y accelerates because squaring makes big numbers even bigger. 
            This makes the curve steep and creates the classic parabola.
            <br> <br>
           <i> Watch</i>: <a href="https://youtu.be/Tu_BcYfmKZo?si=JjetuarRKGa5g0bY">
            Why Quadratics Make a Parabola </a>
            
        </p>

        <h2>The Vertex</h2>
        <p>
            The turning point of the parabola is called the <strong>vertex</strong>, at:
            <span class="highlight">h = -b / (2a)</span>,
            <span class="highlight">k = a(h)² + b(h) + c</span>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <a href="https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/vertex-of-a-parabola/" >vertex</a>
           is the point where the slope is zero and the curve switches from rising to falling or vice versa (i.e. slope of derivative behavior changes).<br>
           A polynomial of degree n can have at most n-1  turning points.
           There's NO strict maximum degree of the polynomial— the degree could be any number ≥ n.
        </p>

        <h2> The Roots (x-intercepts)</h2>
        <p>
            To find where the parabola crosses the x-axis (<span class="highlight">y = 0</span>), i.e. it's <strong><a href="https://www.cuemath.com/algebra/roots-of-quadratic-equation/" >roots </a></strong>
            we use the quadratic formula:
        </p>
        <p>
            <span class="highlight">x = (-b ± √(b² - 4ac)) / (2a)</span>
        </p>
        <p>
        <ul>
            <li> If the <strong><a href="https://www.nku.edu/~longa/classes/biomath/www.biology.arizona.edu/biomath/tutorials/Quadratic/Roots.html#:~:text=If%20the%20discriminant%20of%20a,not%20intersect%20the%20x%2Daxis." >discriminant</a></strong> (<span class="highlight">b² - 4ac</span>) is positive, there are two real roots.</li>
         <li>    If it's zero, there's one real root (touching the x-axis).</li>
          <li>  If it's negative, there are no real roots (the parabola floats above or below the x-axis).</li>
        </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
        <i><u> The <a href="https://www.cuemath.com/algebra/descartes-rule-of-signs/" >maximum number of roots</a> of a quadratic function is <strong>TWO</strong></u></i> 
        </p>
        <div class="summary">
            In summary, quadratic functions form parabolas because of the squaring of x, which makes the change in y accelerate
            and creates symmetry around a vertical axis!
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h1>Quadratic Function Visualirer: <br>
    <code> <strong> y = ax² + bx + c  </strong> </code> </h1>
    <canvas id="canvas"></canvas>
    <div id="equation">Equation: y = x²</div>

    <div class="controls">
        <label>a: <input type="range" id="a" min="-5" max="5" step="0.1" value="1"></label>
        <label>b: <input type="range" id="b" min="-10" max="10" step="0.1" value="0"></label>
        <label>c: <input type="range" id="c" min="-10" max="10" step="0.1" value="0"></label>
    </div>
